        <h2>Pricing deep dive</h2>

        <h3>Raken</h3>
        <p>Pro plan: ~$15/user/month. Business plan: ~$19/user/month. Enterprise: custom. For a 10-person field team on the Business plan, you're looking at ~$190/month. For 25 users, ~$475/month. The per-user model scales up quickly.</p>

        <h3>Contractor Foreman</h3>
        <p>Basic: $49/month, Standard: $99/month, Plus: $149/month, Pro: $199/month, Unlimited: $249/month. All plans include unlimited users — you pay for features, not headcount. For a 25-person team, Contractor Foreman is significantly cheaper than Raken at comparable feature tiers.</p>

        <p><strong>The pricing reality:</strong> For small teams (under 5 users), Raken is actually competitive. For medium teams (10–30 users), Contractor Foreman's flat pricing is a clear cost advantage — especially since you get a full PM platform for less than Raken's field-reporting-only subscription.</p>

        <h2>Where Raken is superior</h2>

        <h3>Daily report quality and compliance</h3>
        <p>Raken's daily reports are simply better than Contractor Foreman's. The mobile workflow is designed around field staff who are reluctant to do paperwork — short, structured prompts that take 3–5 minutes. Auto-populated weather from GPS location. Automatic photo attachment to reports. The result is higher completion rates and more legally defensible records.</p>

        <p>For contractors in industries or markets where daily report compliance is scrutinized — commercial projects with owners who require daily logs, projects with insurance implications, government work — Raken's documentation quality justifies the cost even if you're paying more per user.</p>

        <h3>Safety tools</h3>
        <p>Raken's Business plan includes toolbox talk tracking, safety observation forms, near-miss reporting, and a library of pre-built safety topics. This is purpose-built for safety-conscious commercial contractors and meets the documentation expectations of safety auditors. Contractor Foreman has basic safety logging but doesn't match this depth.</p>

        <h3>Subcontractor reporting integration</h3>
        <p>Raken allows GCs to require subs to submit daily reports through the platform, creating a consolidated project log that includes all parties. When a dispute arises about what a sub's crew did on a particular day, the sub's Raken daily report is on record. Contractor Foreman doesn't have a comparable subcontractor reporting workflow.</p>

        <h3>Production tracking</h3>
        <p>Raken's production tracking feature lets field teams log quantities of work completed — linear feet of pipe installed, cubic yards of concrete poured, squares of roofing completed — against estimated quantities. This gives project managers real-time production efficiency data, not just a narrative log. It's a feature that commercial estimators and project managers find valuable for future bidding and scheduling. Contractor Foreman doesn't have this.</p>

        <h2>Where Contractor Foreman is superior</h2>

        <h3>Complete project management at low cost</h3>
        <p>Contractor Foreman does Gantt scheduling, estimating, budgeting, job costing, client portals, punch lists, invoicing, and time tracking — plus daily reports — for $49–$249/month for unlimited users. It's the most feature-complete budget construction PM platform available. If you currently have no PM software and need everything, Contractor Foreman is a remarkable value.</p>

        <h3>Financial management</h3>
        <p>Raken has no financial management capabilities — no estimates, no budgets, no invoices. Contractor Foreman has all of these, with QuickBooks and other accounting integrations. For contractors who want field documentation and financial management in one system, Contractor Foreman is the logical choice.</p>

        <h3>Flat-rate pricing for growing teams</h3>
        <p>As your headcount grows, Contractor Foreman's flat pricing becomes increasingly advantageous. Adding an employee to Raken means another $15–$19/month; adding them to Contractor Foreman is free. For companies scaling from 10 to 30 to 50 employees, this difference is material.</p>

        <h2>Can you use both?</h2>
        <p>Some contractors use Contractor Foreman for project management and scheduling while using Raken specifically for daily reports and safety documentation. This combination makes sense if:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>You have a commercial project requiring high-quality daily report compliance</li>
          <li>Your company's safety program requires toolbox talk tracking and near-miss documentation</li>
          <li>You already use Contractor Foreman but the daily report quality isn't meeting GC requirements</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The dual-platform approach adds cost and introduces some data silos, but for contractors where safety and compliance documentation is a serious business requirement, it can be worth it.</p>

        <h2>Bottom line</h2>
        <p>Choose Raken if daily report quality, safety compliance, and field documentation are your primary needs, and your team is small enough that the per-user cost is manageable. Choose Contractor Foreman if you need a complete PM platform at the lowest possible price, and good-enough daily reports are acceptable.</p>

